TUBERCULOSIS, BOVINE - PANAMA
*****************************
Date: Fri, 18 Jul 1997 13:57:09 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@usa.healthnet.org>
Via: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: Emergency report-Translation of an e-mail received on 15 July 1997
from Dr Y.I. Romero de Rodriguez, Director of the National Animal Health
Service, Ministry of Agricultural Development and Animal Production, Panama:
Nature of diagnosis: post-mortem, laboratory and tuberculin tests.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 26 June 1997.
Location: Bocas del Toro Province
No. of outbreaks: 1

Description of affected population: a mixed production unit with cattle,
buffaloes and equids.
The 13 animals affected were extensively grazed zebus for slaughter.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible 6,192*
cases 13
deaths ...
destroyed ...
slaughtered ...

* 5,257 cattle, 800 buffaloes, 135 equids.
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Veterinary Research and Diagnostic
Laboratory, Ministry of Agricultural Development and Animal Production.
B. Diagnostic tests used: microbiological, histopathological, immunological.
C. Causal agent: Mycobacterium bovis.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent/origin of infection: the disease was probably present
in the affected herd in a chronic form, since 51 of the 491 animals tested
reacted to the intradermal tuberculin test.
B. Mode of spread: by respiratory and digestive route.
C. Other epidemiological details: animals living in a rural area on land
that is often flooded. Absence of official abattoirs in the region.
Control measures during reporting period: partial stamping-out, control
programme for the whole country, quarantine, movement control and other
precautions at frontiers and inside the country, testing, notifiable disease.
